---
import UseCaseLayout from '../../layouts/UseCaseLayout.astro';
import data from '../../data/design-systems.json';
import PrincipleNav from '../../components/PrincipleNav.astro';
import Markdown from '../../components/Markdown.astro';
import Usage from '../../components/Usage.astro';
import UsageItem from '../../components/UsageItem.astro';
import Bibliography from '../../components/Bibliography.astro';
import BibliographyItem from '../../components/BibliographyItem.astro';
import BibliographySection from '../../components/BibliographySection.astro';

const principle = data.principles.find((p) => p.id === 'accessibility-as-a-baseline')!;
const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const sectionPath = '/design-systems';
---

<UseCaseLayout
  title={`${principle.title} - Design Systems`}
  principle={principle}
  categoryColors={data.categoryColors}
  sectionName={data.title}
  sectionPath="/design-systems"
>
  <article class="grid gap-600">
    <Markdown
      content={`
Accessibility is not an enhancement.
It is the **baseline quality bar** of a design system.

When accessibility is treated as optional, it is postponed, fragmented,
or removed under pressure.
When treated as a baseline, it becomes invisible, reliable, and scalable.
    `}
    />

    <Markdown
      content={`
## Approach

---

#### Design accessible by default

Accessibility should be built into foundations and components from the start.
    `}
    />

    <Usage>
      <UsageItem variant="do">
        Use accessible color contrast as a non-negotiable constraint.
      </UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">Rely on manual fixes after components are shipped.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Define focus, hover, and active states consistently.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">Leave interactive states undefined.</UsageItem>
    </Usage>

    <Markdown
      content={`
#### Encode accessibility into components

Accessibility should be expressed through behavior, not documentation alone.
    `}
    />

    <Usage>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Bake ARIA roles and keyboard support into components.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">Expect consumers to add accessibility features manually.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Provide accessible defaults that work out of the box.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">
        Ship components that require extra effort to be accessible.
      </UsageItem>
    </Usage>

    <Markdown
      content={`
#### Treat accessibility as a system concern

Accessibility issues multiply when handled at the product level.
    `}
    />

    <Usage>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Centralize accessibility patterns and decisions.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">
        Solve the same accessibility problem in multiple products.
      </UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Document accessibility guarantees per component.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">Leave accessibility expectations implicit.</UsageItem>
    </Usage>

    <Markdown
      content={`
#### Test and validate continuously

Accessibility is not static and must be maintained over time.
    `}
    />

    <Usage>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Include keyboard and screen reader testing in reviews.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">Assume accessibility remains intact by default.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="do">Use automated checks to catch regressions.</UsageItem>
      <UsageItem variant="dont">Rely solely on manual audits.</UsageItem>
    </Usage>

    <Markdown
      content={`
#### Why this principle matters

Accessibility as a baseline ensures inclusivity, legal compliance,
and long-term system resilience.

When accessibility is built into the system,
teams move faster because they donâ€™t have to re-solve the same problems.
    `}
    />
  </article>

  <Bibliography
    opener="Accessibility as a baseline is supported by standards, inclusive design practices, and system-level thinking:"
    closer="These sources explain why accessibility must be foundational rather than optional."
  >
    <BibliographySection type="books">
      <BibliographyItem
        author="Heydon Pickering"
        title="Inclusive Design Patterns"
        description="Practical guidance on building accessible UI patterns."
        url="https://inclusive-components.design/"
      />
      <BibliographyItem
        author="Steve Krug"
        title="Don't Make Me Think (Revisited)"
        description="Highlights usability and accessibility as core quality attributes."
        url="https://sensible.com/dont-make-me-think/"
      />
      <BibliographyItem
        author="Sarah Horton & Whitney Quesenbery"
        title="A Web for Everyone"
        description="Explains inclusive design principles and accessibility foundations."
        url="https://rosenfeldmedia.com/books/a-web-for-everyone/"
      />
    </BibliographySection>

    <BibliographySection type="urls">
      <BibliographyItem
        author="W3C"
        title="Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)"
        description="The global standard for accessible digital experiences."
        url="https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/wcag/"
      />
      <BibliographyItem
        author="GOV.UK"
        title="Accessibility in Design Systems"
        description="Shows how accessibility is treated as a baseline in a public-sector system."
        url="https://design-system.service.gov.uk/accessibility/"
      />
      <BibliographyItem
        author="NNGroup"
        title="Accessibility Is Not Optional"
        description="Explains why accessibility must be built into UX from the start."
        url="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/accessibility-not-optional/"
      />
    </BibliographySection>
  </Bibliography>

  <PrincipleNav
    baseUrl={baseUrl}
    currentPrincipleId={principle.id}
    sectionPath={sectionPath}
    allPrinciples={data.principles}
  />
</UseCaseLayout>
